<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" label="direct-integration">
	<title> Direct Integration </title>

	<introduction>
		
		<p>
			Solving a differential equation might sound like a new challenge, but you've actually done it before, in calculus! Any time you find an antiderivative, you're solving a differential equation.
		</p>

		<p>
			In this section, we'll reframe antiderivatives as solutions to differential equations and use this perspective to introduce our first method: direct integration. By the end, you'll be able to find general and particular solutions to simple differential equations using integration.
		</p>
	
	</introduction>

	<task label="review-direct-integration-1">
		<title> ü§îüí≠ Review Question: Recall from Calculus.. </title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Suppose you saw the following expression from calculus:
				<me>
					\frac{dy}{dx} = x^3 - 7.
				</me>
				Select all of the true statements.
			</p>
		</statement>

		<choices randomize="yes">
			<choice correct="no">
				<statement><m>\quad y</m> is the derivative of <m>x^3 - 7</m></statement>
				<feedback>Saying <m>y</m> is the derivative of <m>x^3 - 7</m>, is the same as <m>\left(x^3 - 7\right)' = y</m></feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="yes">
				<statement><m>\quad x^3 - 7</m> is the derivative of <m>y</m></statement>
				<feedback>This one should be the most straight forward.</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="yes">
				<statement><m>\quad y</m> is the antiderivative of <m>x^3 - 7</m></statement>
				<feedback>Saying <m>y</m> is the antiderivative of <m>x^3 - 7</m> is the same thing as saying <q>when you take the derivative of <m>y</m> you shoud get <m>x^3 - 7</m></q></feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="no">
				<statement><m>\quad x^3 - 7</m> is the antiderivative of <m>y</m></statement>
				<feedback>Saying <m>x^3 - 7</m> is the antiderivative of <m>y</m> is the same as saying <q>when you take the derivative of <m>x^3 - 7</m> you should get <m>y</m></q>, which is not true.</feedback>
			</choice>
		</choices>
	</task>

	<paragraphs label="antiderivatives">
		<title> üì∞ Antiderivatives </title>

		<p>
			You might not realize it, but solving some differential equations is a skill you already have! For instance, computing the antiderivative of <m>x^2</m> means you're finding a function <m>y</m> whose derivative is <m>x^2</m>. In other words:
		</p>

		<blockquote>
			<p>
				<q>Find <m>y</m> such that the derivative of <m>y</m> is <m>x^2</m>.</q>
			</p>
		</blockquote>

		<p>
			This is exactly the same as solving the differential equation:
		</p>

		<blockquote>
			<p>
				<q>Find <m>y</m> such that <m>\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = x^2</m>.</q>
			</p>
		</blockquote>

		<p>
			To solve this, we integrate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>:
		</p>

		<md>
			<mrow> \int\frac{d}{dx}[y]\ dx \amp = \int x^2\ dx </mrow>
			<mrow> y + c_1 \amp = \frac{1}{3} x^3 + c_2 </mrow>
			<mrow> y \amp = \frac{1}{3} x^3 + (c_2 - c_1) = \frac{1}{3} x^3 + c </mrow>
		</md>
		
		<p>
			The constant <m>c = c_2 - c_1</m> absorbs the difference between the two integration constants. This is a standard simplification when solving differential equations.
		</p>

		<me>
			y = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + c
		</me>

		<task label="chkpt-antiderivatives-2">
			<title>  üìñ‚ùì When it Comes to Constants, Less is More </title>
			<statement>Combining constants is a common practice in differential equations.</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement> True</statement>
					<feedback>Correct! Combining constants is an easy way to simplify a solution and is a standard practice in differential equations.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>False</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect, revisit the examples above.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<p>
			Now let's look at a slightly more involved example.
		</p>
		
		<example><title> Isolate <m>y</m> </title>
			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the function, <m>y</m>, such that
						<me>
							2y' - 4\sin x = 2
						</me>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</p>

			<solution>
				<p>
					This is another antiderivative problem where we first have to isolate <m>y'</m> before integrating, like so
				</p>
				
				<me>
					y' = 1 + 2 \sin x
				</me>.
				
				<p>
					This equation now says <q>The unknown <m>y</m> is the function whose derivative is <m>1 + 2 \sin x</m></q> or, in other words,
				</p>

				<blockquote>
					<p>
						<q>The unknown <m>y</m> is the antiderivative of <m>1 + 2 \sin x</m></q>.
					</p>
				</blockquote>

				<p>
					Instead of writing down the antiderivative as our solution, let's take the differential equations approach and integrate both sides of the equation with respect to <m>x</m>
				</p>
				
				<md>
					<mrow> \int y'\ dx 	\amp = \int \left(1 + 2 \sin x\right) \ dx 				</mrow>
					<mrow> 	y + c_1 	\amp = x - 2 \cos x + c_2 								</mrow>
					<mrow> 			y 	\amp = x - 2 \cos x + \boxed{c_2 - c_1}\leftarrow c		</mrow>
					<mrow> 		y(x)	\amp  = x - 2 \cos x + c 								</mrow>.
				</md>
				
				<p>
					As before, the constants of integration are combined into a single constant <m>c</m>. This practice of merging constants is standard in solving differential equations and simplifies the final result.
				</p>

			</solution>
		
		</example>
	
		<task label="chkpt-antiderivatives-3">
			<title>  üìñ‚ùì Finding <m>y</m> </title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Solving for <m>y</m> in the equation
					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dx} = \ln(3x+1)
					</me>
					amounts to finding the antiderivative of <m>\ln(3x+1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement> True</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct, integrating both sides gives
							<me>
								y = \int \ln(3x+1)\ dx \quad \leftarrow \text{anti-derivative of } \ln(3x+1)
							</me>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>False</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>

		</task>

		<p>
			In summary, solving simple differential equations often reduces to finding the antiderivative of a function. By integrating both sides and simplifying constants, you can find the general solution.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<fact label="antiderivatives-cyu">
		<statement>
			<p>
				<task label="chkpt-antiderivatives-4"><title> Select-the-Best-Answer </title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							How could you solve for <m>y</m> in the equation
							<me>
								\frac12\frac{dy}{dx} - \tan(2x) = x
							</me>?
						</p>
					</statement>

					<choices randomize="yes">
						<choice>
							<statement>Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.</statement>
							<feedback>Incorrect, differentiating both sides only puts another derivative on <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m>.</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>Isolate <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> and integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.</statement>
							<feedback>Correct!</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>Isolate <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> and integrating both sides with respect to <m>y</m>.</statement>
							<feedback>Incorrect, the integration is not with respect to <m>y</m>.</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>Find the antiderivative of <m>\tan(2x)</m>.</statement>
							<feedback>Incorrect, the solution is the antiderivative of <m>2\tan(2x) + 2x</m>, not just <m>\tan(2x)</m>.</feedback>
						</choice>
					</choices>

				</task>

				<task label="chkpt-antiderivatives-5"><title> <em>Select-the-Best-Answer</em> </title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							The solution to the differential equation
							<me>
								\frac13 y'- 7x + x^2 = 1
							</me>
							is the antiderivative of which function?
						</p>
					</statement>

					<choices randomize="yes">
						
						<choice>
							<statement><m>\quad y</m></statement>
							<feedback>Incorrect. <m>y</m> is the solution to the differential equation.</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement><m>\quad 21x - 3x^2 + 1</m></statement>
							<feedback>Incorrect, perhaps check your algebra.</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement><m>\quad 7x - x^2 - 1</m></statement>
							<feedback>Incorrect, perhaps check your algebra.</feedback>
						</choice>

						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement><m>\quad 21x - 3x^2 + 3</m></statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct! Isolating <m>y'</m> gives
									<me>
										y' = 21x - 3x^2 + 3
									</me>,
									so the solution is the antiderivative of <m>21x - 3x^2 + 3</m>.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>

					</choices>

				</task>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</fact>

	<paragraphs label="solving-via-direct-integration">
		<title> üì∞ Solving Differential Equations via Direct Integration </title>

		<p>
			We've seen that when you can isolate the derivative of <m>y</m> in the form:
			<me>
				\frac{d}{dx}[y] = f(x)
			</me>
			you can solve the equation by integrating both sides. This idea also applies to more general equations where the derivative involves both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>:
			<me>
				\frac{d}{dx}\left[g(x,y)\right] = f(x)
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Here, <m>f(x)</m> must depend only on <m>x</m>, and <m>g(x,y)</m> may involve both variables. This structure allows us to apply our first solution technique: <em>direct integration</em>.
		</p>

		<exploration xml:id="direct-integration">
			<title> Direct Integration </title>
			<p>
				To solve a differential equation of the form
				<men xml:id="direct-integration-equation">
					\frac{d}{dx}\left[g(x,y)\right] = f(x)
				</men>,
				follow these steps:
				<dl>
					<li xml:id="di-step-1"><title> Integrate Both Sides </title>
						<p>
							Apply integration with respect to <m>x</m> to eliminate the derivative.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="di-step-2"><title> Solve for <m>y</m> </title>
						<p>
							After integration, isolate <m>y</m> to get the general solution.
						</p>
					</li>
				</dl>
			</p>
		</exploration>

		<p label="direct-integration-chkpt-bundle">
			<task label="chkpt-direct-integration-2">
				<title>  üìñ‚ùì Does Direct Integration Apply? </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Direct integration could be used to solve the equation
						<me>
							\frac{d}{dx}\left[y^2 + x^3\right] = \sqrt{x}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement> True</statement>
						<feedback>Correct!</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>False</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. This equation is in the form <xref ref="direct-integration-equation"/>.</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-direct-integration-3">
				<title>  üìñ‚ùì Why Doesn't Direct Integration Apply Here? </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Give the reason direct integration cannot be applied to the equation
						<me>
							\frac{d}{dx}\left[\frac{x}{y^2}\right] = \sin(x+y)
						</me>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice>
						<statement>There is a fraction in the derivative.</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect, direct integration doesn't care about fractions.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>The <m>y</m> term is squared.</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect, direct integration can handle this.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>There is a sine term on the right side of the equation.</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect, the sine is not the issue here.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>The right-hand side contains <m>y</m>.</statement>
						<feedback>Correct! Direct integration only works when the right-hand side contains only the independent variable, in this case <m>x</m>.</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>
		</p>

		<p>
			Consider the following examples to see how this approach applies to some more interesting problems.
		</p>

		<example xml:id="direct-integration-example-1"><title> Integrate both sides to Recover <m>y</m> </title>
		
			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the particular solution to the differential equation
						<me>
							\frac{d}{dx}\left[5x \cdot y\right] = \frac{1}{x^2} , \quad y\left(1\right) = -4
						</me>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</p>
			<solution>

				<p>
					First, observe that this problem is in the form
					<me>
						\frac{d}{dx}\left[g(x,y)\right] = f(x)
					</me>
					where
					<me>
						g(x,y) = 5x \cdot y \quad \text{ and } \quad f(x) = \frac{1}{x^2}
					</me>.
				</p>
				<p>
					So, we can solve for <m>y</m> using direct integration:
				</p>

				<p>
					<term> <xref ref="di-step-1" text="custom">Step 1: Integrate both Sides</xref> </term>
				</p>

				<p>
					Integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>, we get
					<md>
						<mrow> \int \frac{d}{dx}\left[5x \cdot y\right]\ dx \amp = \int x^{-2}\ dx </mrow>
						<mrow> 5x \cdot y + c_1 \amp = -x^{-1} + c_2 </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					<term> <xref ref="di-step-2" text="custom">Step 2: Isolate the Solution</xref> </term>
				</p>

				<p>
					Now that the dependent variable <m>y</m> is free from the derivative, we can isolate it to find the general solution, as follows
					<md>
						<mrow>  y \amp = \frac{1}{5x}\Big(-\frac{1}{x} + \overset{=\ c}{\overbrace{c_2 - c_1}}\Big) </mrow>
						<mrow>  y \amp = \frac{1}{5x}\left(-\frac{1}{x} + c\right) \quad \leftarrow \ \text{general solution}</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					Since we are given the condition <m>y\left(1\right) = -4</m>, we need to find <m>c</m>.
					<md>
						<mrow>  -4	\amp = \frac{1}{5}\left(-1 + c\right)\qquad \leftarrow \small\text{ multiply both sides by } 5	</mrow>
						<mrow>  -20	\amp = -1 + c \quad \implies \quad c = -19	</mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, the particular solution (for <m>c=-19</m>) is
					<me>
						y = \frac{1}{5x}\left(-\frac{1}{x} - 19\right)
					</me>.
				</p>

			</solution>

		</example>

		<task label="chkpt-direct-integration-4">
			<title>  üìñ‚ùì First Step </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					In the differential equation
					<me>
						\frac{d}{dx}\left[5x \cdot y\right] = \frac{1}{x^2}
					</me>,
					what is the first step in solving for <m>y</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>Release <m>y</m> by integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.</statement>
					<feedback>Correct! Integrating both sides is the first step in solving for <m>y</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>Release <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> by integrating both sides with respect to <m>y</m>.</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. Integrating both sides with respect to <m>y</m> would not eliminate the derivative since the derivative is with respect to <m>x</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>Compute the derivative of <m>5x \cdot y</m> using the product rule.</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. This would actually make the equation more complicated.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>Isolate <m>x</m>.</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. This would not help solve for <m>y</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<example xml:id="direct-integration-example-2"><title> Isolate the Derivative before Integrating </title>
			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute the general solution of the differential equation
						<me>
							\frac{1}{\cos x}\frac{d}{dx}\Big[y\sin(2x)\Big] - 1 = \sec x
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</p>
			<solution>
				<p>
					First, we get the derivative by itself on the left-hand side
					<aside><title> ‚òùÔ∏è Recall the Identity </title>
						<p>
							<me>
								\sec x = \frac{1}{\cos x}
							</me>
						</p>
					</aside>
					<md>
						<mrow>
							\frac{d}{dx}\Big[ y \sin(2x) \Big] \amp = \cos x\left( 1 + \frac{1}{\cos x} \right)
						</mrow>
						<mrow>
							\frac{d}{dx}\Big[
								\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{g(x,y)}}{\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\uparrow}}{\ul{y\sin(2x)}}}
							\Big] \amp = \us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{f(x)}}{\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\uparrow}}{\ul{\cos x + 1}}}
						</mrow>
					</md>
					Now, we integrate by sides with respect to <m>x</m>, releasing <m>y</m> from the derivative and allowing us to isolate the general solution.
					<md>
						<mrow>	\int \frac{d}{dx}\Big[y\sin(2x)\Big]dx	\amp = \int \left(\cos x + 1\right) \ dx	</mrow>
						<mrow>							y\sin(2x) + c_1	\amp = \sin x + x + c_2						</mrow>
						<mrow>										y	\amp = \frac{\sin x + x + c}{\sin(2x)}
																					\qquad (c = c_2 - c_1)
						</mrow>
					</md>.
				</p>
			</solution>

		</example>

		<p>
			Direct integration is one of the simplest techniques for solving differential equations, provided the structure allows it. If you can isolate a derivative of <m>y</m> or an expression involving <m>y</m> and the right-hand side depends only on <m>x</m>, you're in business. Just integrate both sides and solve for <m>y</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			This approach highlights how closely tied differential equations are to the core ideas of calculus.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<fact label="direct-integration-cyu">
		<statement>
			<p>
				Given the differential equation
				<men xml:id="direct-integration-cyu-eqn">
					y'= e^{2t} - 4t,
				</men>
				answer the following questions:
				<task label="chkpt-direct-integration-5">
					<title> Identify the Variables </title>
						<statement>
							<p>
								The dependent variable in equation <xref ref="direct-integration-cyu-eqn"/> is <fillin width="2" mode="string" answer="y" />.
							</p>

							<p>
								The independent variable in equation <xref ref="direct-integration-cyu-eqn"/> is <fillin width="2" mode="string" answer="t" />.
							</p>
						</statement>
						
						<evaluation>
							<evaluate>
								<test correct="yes">
									<strcmp>\s*y\s*</strcmp>
									<feedback>Yes, the dependent variable is <m>y</m>.</feedback>
								</test>
								<test>
									<strcmp>\s*Y\s*</strcmp>
									<feedback>No, <m>Y</m> is not the same as <m>y</m>.</feedback>
								</test>
								<test>
									<strcmp>\s*t|T\s*</strcmp>
									<feedback>No, <m>t</m> is not the dependent variable.</feedback>
								</test>
								<test>
									<strcmp>.*</strcmp>
									<feedback>Incorrect. Carefully review the topic of "dependent and independent variables".</feedback>
								</test>
							</evaluate>
							<evaluate>
								<test correct="yes">
									<strcmp>\s*t\s*</strcmp>
									<feedback>Yes, the independent variable is <m>t</m>.</feedback>
								</test>
								<test>
									<strcmp>\s*T\s*</strcmp>
									<feedback>No, <m>T</m> is not the same as <m>t</m>.</feedback>
								</test>
								<test>
									<strcmp>\s*y|Y\s*</strcmp>
									<feedback>No, <m>y</m> is not the independent variable.</feedback>
								</test>
								<test>
									<strcmp>.*</strcmp>
									<feedback>Incorrect. Carefully review the topic of "dependent and independent variables".</feedback>
								</test>
							</evaluate>	
						</evaluation>
				</task>
				<task label="chkpt-direct-integration-6"><title> Select-the-Best-Answer </title>

					<introduction>
						<p>
							Give the general solution to equation <xref ref="direct-integration-cyu-eqn"/>.
						</p>
						<p>
							<em>Press</em> <c>Activate</c> <em>to submit your answer.</em>
						</p>
					</introduction>
						
					<webwork xml:id="p2-c1-s2-i5-ww">
						<pg-code>
							Context()->variables->add(t => 'Real', y => 'Real');
							$ans = FormulaUpToConstant("1/2 e^{2t} - 2 t^2");
						</pg-code>

						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>y(t) = </m> <var name="$ans" width="25" />
							</p>
							<p>
								<em>Don't forget the constant of integration. Do not use scripts on the constant (e.g., <m>c_2</m>).</em>
							</p>
						</statement>
					</webwork>

				</task>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</fact>

	<paragraphs label="direct-integration-wrapup">
		<title> üóùÔ∏è Key Takeaways </title>
		<p>
			<aside><title>üéß Listen</title><p><audio source="audio/readings/c1/template.mp3" width="100%" /></p></aside>
			<ul marker="square">
				<li>
					<p>
						When you can rearrange a differential equation so that a derivative is isolated on one side and equals a function of the independent variable, like
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \quad\text{or}\quad 
							\frac{d}{dx}\left[x^2\cos(y)\right] = f(x)
						</me>
						the next step is to integrate both sides of the equation.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Doing so removes the derivative and allows you to isolate the unknown function <m>y</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						This process is called <em>direct integration</em>. It's the simplest method for solving differential equations, and it lays the foundation for many techniques you'll learn later.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ul>
		</p>
